# Before starting work

- Run `mai context <file>` on files you'll touch — see tickets, warnings, constraints, review findings.
- Run `mai expand <prompt>` to resolve any `[[refs]]` in your task description.

# Post-task checklist

After every task:

- [ ] Run `mai check` — all `[[refs]]` in notes and `// @mai:` code refs must resolve
- [ ] Close tickets you resolved: `mai close <id> -m "summary"`
- [ ] Leave warnings for fragile code: `mai warn <path> "what to watch out for"`

# Commands

```bash
mai show <id>                   # read a ticket/note
mai ls                          # open work queue
mai context <path>              # everything about a file
mai check                       # validate all refs
mai refs <id>                   # find what references a note
mai expand "text with [[refs]]" # resolve refs with context
mai ready                       # unblocked work
mai blocked                     # stuck on deps
```

# Linking code to notes

Annotate source code with `// @mai:` comments to tie implementation to tickets, decisions, or docs:

```typescript
// @mai: [[tre-5c4a]]
export function refreshToken() {
  // ...
}
```

```python
# @mai: [[architecture#Auth]]
def validate_token():
    ...
```

```rust
// @mai: [[tre-5c4a]]
fn refresh_token() {
    // ...
}
```

`mai check` validates these resolve. `mai refs <id>` finds all code referencing a note.

# Wiki links in notes

Note bodies can reference other notes with `[[note-id]]`:

```bash
mai add-note tre-5c4a "See [[wrn-a4f2]] for the race condition warning"
```

`mai check` validates these too. `mai expand` resolves them with context for agents.
